    "recap_headline": "Seton Hall University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "South Orange, N.J. \u2013\nThe Hall broke out the bats on Tuesday afternoon, putting 14 runs on the board in a 14-1 midweek victory over Wagner at Mike Sheppard Sr. Stadium.\nHow it Happened\nThe Pirate bats got right to work in the bottom of the first, quickly loading the bases with nobody out.\nRyan Frontera\nknocked home the first two runs of the game with a two-run single to left, spotting Seton Hall an early edge. Three batters later,\nFrankie Scrivanic\nsingled home the third tally of the frame for the home side.\nAfter the Pirates left two runners on in the second, they capitalized in a big way in the third. With two outs and the bases once again loaded,\nGabe Cavazzoni\nripped a two-run double down the left field line to stretch the lead up to 5-0. Later in the inning with the bases juiced once again,\nAidan Sengenberger\nhit a double to right field which cleared the bases and gave Seton Hall an 8-0 advantage.\nPirate starter\nJason Kuhn\ncontinued to cruise on the mound after being spotted the big lead. The freshman earned his first career win by throwing five shutout innings, allowing just two hits and striking out four.\nThe ninth run for the Pirates came across in the fourth on a ground ball from\nVincent Duffy\n. In the fifth, four more Pirates would cross home plate as the home side continued to stretch the lead. Frontera added his third RBI of the game with a double to right, scoring\nJake Lopez\nand getting Seton Hall to double digits, 10-0. After an RBI groundout from\nTy Acker\ngot The Hall its 11\nth\nrun, freshman\nRyan Strnad\ncame up as a pinch hitter and singled home two runs to give the Pirates a 13-0 lead. The final run of the afternoon for Seton Hall would come across in the bottom of the sixth as a wild pitch with the bases loaded allowed Lopez to trot home from third.\nUp Next\nSeton Hall opens a three-game weekend series with Hofstra on Friday afternoon at 4 p.m."
